{"id":"1710.00991","submitter":"Jose Antonio Oller","authors":"J.A. Oller","title":"New results from a number operator interpretation of the compositeness\n  of bound and resonant states","comments":"35 pages, 4 figures. To match the published version","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.aop.2018.07.023","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph hep-lat hep-th nucl-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A novel theoretical approach to the problem of the compositeness ($X$) of a\nresonance or bound state is developed on the basis of the expectation values of\nthe number operators of the free particles in the continuum. This formalism is\nspecially suitable for effective field theories in which the bare elementary\nstates are integrated out but that give rise to resonance and bound states when\nimplemented in nonperturbative calculations. We demonstrate that $X=1$ for\nfinite-range energy-independent potentials, either regular or singular. A\nnon-trivial example for an energy-dependent potential is discussed where it is\nshown that $X$ is independent of any type of cutoff regulator employed. The\ngeneralization of these techniques to relativistic states is developed. We also\nexplain how to obtain a meaningful compositeness with respect to the open\nchannels for resonances, even if it is complex in a first turn, by making use\nof suitable phase-factor transformations. Defining elementariness as $X=0$, we\nderive a new universal criterion for the elementariness of a bound state. Along\nthe same lines, a necessary condition for a resonance to be qualified as\nelementary is given. The application of the formalism here developed might be\nof considerable practical interest.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Oct 2017 05:27:37 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 14 Nov 2017 07:53:11 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 26 Jul 2018 18:31:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-15"}
{"id":"1710.00992","submitter":"Rebecca Faust","authors":"Rebecca Faust, David Glickenstein, Carlos Scheidegger","title":"DimReader: Axis lines that explain non-linear projections","comments":"13 Pages, 12 Figures","journal-ref":"IEEE transactions on visualization and computer graphics 25.1\n  (2018): 481-490","doi":"10.1109/TVCG.2018.2865194","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.HC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Non-linear dimensionality reduction (NDR) methods such as LLE and t-SNE are\npopular with visualization researchers and experienced data analysts, but\npresent serious problems of interpretation. In this paper, we present\nDimReader, a technique that recovers readable axes from such techniques.\nDimReader is based on analyzing infinitesimal perturbations of the dataset with\nrespect to variables of interest. The perturbations define exactly how we want\nto change each point in the original dataset and we measure the effect that\nthese changes have on the projection. The recovered axes are in direct analogy\nwith the axis lines (grid lines) of traditional scatterplots. We also present\nmethods for discovering perturbations on the input data that change the\nprojection the most. The calculation of the perturbations is efficient and\neasily integrated into programs written in modern programming languages. We\npresent results of DimReader on a variety of NDR methods and datasets both\nsynthetic and real-life, and show how it can be used to compare different NDR\nmethods. Finally, we discuss limitations of our proposal and situations where\nfurther research is needed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Oct 2017 05:28:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 31 Jul 2018 02:33:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-08"}
